# Full Program

Type this yourself.

```python
print("=" * 50)
print("      DELETE PATIENT RECORD")
print("=" * 50)

hospital = []

total = int(input("Enter total patients: "))

for i in range(total):

    patient = {}

    patient["Name"] = input("Enter Name: ").strip().upper()
    patient["Age"] = int(input("Enter Age: "))
    patient["Blood Group"] = input("Enter Blood Group: ").strip().upper()

    hospital.append(patient)

print("\nCurrent Patients")

for patient in hospital:
    print(patient)

search_name = input("\nEnter patient name to delete: ").strip().upper()

found = False

for patient in hospital:

    if patient["Name"] == search_name:

        hospital.remove(patient)

        found = True

        print("Patient deleted successfully.")

        break

if found == False:
    print("Patient not found.")

print("\nRemaining Patients")

for patient in hospital:
    print(patient)
```

---

# What Does `remove()` Do?

Suppose we have

```python
hospital = [
    Alice,
    Bob,
    Charlie
]
```

When Python runs

```python
hospital.remove(Bob)
```

The list becomes

```python
hospital = [
    Alice,
    Charlie
]
```

---

# Why do we use `break`?

Suppose two patients accidentally have the same name.

Without `break`, Python will continue searching through the rest of the list even after deleting one patient.

```python
break
```

tells Python:

> "Stop the loop immediately."

